            "description": "<h3>To Labor in Government</h3>\n          <p>Something had gone wrong in the world. There had been a mistake, an error. Someone had decided to pull some awful trick to hurt and humiliate him. It was the only explanation. <br><br>These were the only thoughts that George had as he stared, uncomprehending at the television in his green room at the Reagan building. What was meant to be a victory party to celebrate his stunning re-election against the Democrat Party and the rube Ventura had turned. Staring at splotches of purple dot the map, he felt his heart lurch as though he’d taken a step into the dark and discovered no ground beneath him. Rove had assured him that this was impossible. He had told him that the odds of a deadlock was one in one hundred, one in one thousand. On Fox, the anchors spoke with bewildered tones. They kept flashing video of his campaign rally and the devastated faces within them. <br><br>He couldn’t handle their disappointment. He couldn’t handle their shame. He buried his head in his hands at the thought of the laughing stock this would make him. He’d go out there and they’d stare at him with shock and disgust and—.<br><br>“Sir?”<br><br>George looked up. Standing in the door of his green room stood, not Rove, not his running mate, but Blakes Gottesman—his bag man. The boy, gangly with spots of acne across his weight, shifted nervously. He looked to George like a small toddler trying to inform his parent he needed to use the bathroom.<br><br>“Yeah, Blake?”<br><br>“Sorry for bothering, Mr. President, but um…” George became aware of a phone in the boy’s hand. His mind jumped between a dozen possibilities. “It’s your father. You told me to tell you if he called tonight?”<br><br>George stared at the boy, then at the phone. As if in a dream, he felt the device press itself into his hand. Blake retreated back into the corridor. There was a small click when he took the call off hold.<br><br>“Hi, Poppy,” said George. His voice seemed distant.<br><br>From thousands of miles away came the voice of George’s father. “Well, look at the mess you’ve gotten yourself into now, George. Christ.” There was a long pause. George imagined his father in his study, sipping bourbon and shaking his head at the television. “All that effort, all that money wasted on a thing like this. You know there hasn’t been a contingent since 1800? It’s gonna be an absolute shitshow.”<br><br>“We don’t know that yet, Poppy. There’s… there’s still ballots to count. There could be voter fraud. We could flip a few of these states and get over the—.”<br><br>“Oh don’t give me that horseshit. Voter fraud.” The voice was thin and mocking. “You know, when I didn’t get the nomination in 80, I at least knew how to take the punch. And I managed to get a partial victory out of the thing. I got Reagan to make me Vice President. Eight years. If you had any sense, you’d do the same.”<br><br>George was quiet. He studied his boots. “I’m not sure I get what you’re saying.”<br><br>“Of course you don’t.” A sigh. George redoubled his focus on his shoes, anything to avoid focusing directly  on the voice in his ear. “Look, Gephardt’s a good egg. We know this. He’s our kind of people, not a radical. Hell, there were some days where I felt like I was seeing double with the two of you. Heh.”<br><br>George’s gaze on his boots was intense. In its imperfections, he could see Gephardt’s smug face. Of course! It has been Gephardt’s fault all along. He’d tried to steal his thunder on the war, on taxes, the whole thing. That was the only reason Ventura has succeeded at all. Gephardt had tried to rob George of his office and his honor.<br><br>Poppy continued to prattle on, ignorant of his revelation. “Make a deal. It’ll give us a, uh, a back channel to the White House, a seat at the table when it comes to policy making. You can’t win anyways, the opposition’s too much and all struggling will do is muck up the gears of government. You gotta come out tonight and make it clear you’re not gonna obstruct—.”<br><br>“No.”<br><br>For the first time, Poppy fell silent. Then his voice returned as a low growl. “What do you mean, ‘no.’”<br><br>“I’m gonna fight it out. I’m gonna… I’m gonna… Never surrender. That’s what Rove says. I’m the decider. I’m the commander. I got Zell. I got the capital—.”<br><br>His father’s voice was sharp. He swore he could detect a hint of shock. “George, Christ, would you listen to yourself? All you’re going to do is throw the baby out with the bath water… You could make that… wrestler president. Don’t fucking—. Don’t be a goddamn child. Own up to the situation and—.”<br><br>“I’m not gonna let Gephardt steal the election, Poppy! You’re gonna see! Jeb’s gonna see! Ride or die.”<br><br>His father began to say something else, but George did not hear it. He ended the cal and placed the phone on a table, where it rang useless. <br><br>With a manic cowboy confidence, he strut out of his private chamber and into the hall. With a wild smile, he greeted his aides. He put his arm around Laura and brushed off Rove. He already knew what he wanted to say anyways. Stepping out before the crowd, he could not see their faces. He could not see the future, but he was sure Gephardt had no place in it.</p>",
