            "description": "<h3>Unnecessary and Counterproductive</h3>\n              <p>The mood inside the Reagan Building in downtown DC was funereal. There had been no dropped balloons, no cheers. A few people cried, but most were silent as blue descended upon the map, state by state, locality by locality. A thousand bleary eyes gazed up into the enormous projected face of Brit Hume as he informed viewers that New York had fallen, that Ohio had fallen, that Utah and Alabama had fallen. George W. Bush was on track to become the most dismal failure in America’s history. Worse than McGovern, worse than Mondale, worse than Alf Landon. He had achieved something that no one thought possible. He had won no electoral votes. He had become the worst—.<br><br>In his green room, George W. Bush muted his television and sat watching the images scroll by. There was an image of his campaign rally, the scattered attendees looking pained and miserable. There was a picture of himself, younger, sitting next to his father and Poppy. There was an ad for Non-Drowsy Claritin-D. A woman carrying a tennis racket breathed in heavily and smiled.<br><br>He snorted at the sight. Then his snort turned into a laugh. Then his laugh turned into a series of great, hearty bursts. There were tears in his eyes. They were rolling down his cheeks. The whole thing was absurd. Outrageous. Inconceivable. Not even in his worst nightmares had he imagined such a dismal failure. <br><br>He continued laughing. His career in politics was over. His future was gone. His failure was so enormous, so complete, that it was hard to imagine himself not dragging everyone down with him. Powell and Condi wouldn’t be able to enter a room without people snickering. Cheney would have trouble getting in any room except as a joke. Jeb would be a laughing stock, the man who stole an election for the least successful in American history. Every Bush, his entire family, would be obliterated from the ranks of the Republican Party. <br><br>He was laughing so hard that he was growing light-headed. He couldn’t see the room clearly. He felt high. <br><br>“Blake! Blake!” He called out. “Blake, goddamnit, get your ass in here.”<br><br>There was a creak of the door and his bag man, Blake Gottesman, stepped inside. He looked stricken, either not seeing or refusing to see his wild grin.<br><br>“Blake, give me my phone, I wanna call Poppy.”<br><br>Blake said nothing. He looked at the president with a blank expression.<br><br>George laughed, then got up from his chair. “Phone, Blake. Don’t make me go rooting around in your pockets for it.”<br><br>His bagman opened and shut his mouth fishlike. Then, without a word, he handed the president his phone, and walked out the door, mortified. George did not care. The phone was already ringing. It went to voicemail. He tried a second time and received the same result. On the third, he remained on the line and waited for the beep.<br><br>“Hey, Poppy. It’s Junior. I’m sure you’re in your study right now, watching the results. Maybe you’re even listening to this message right now. Who knows? Wherever you’re at, I just wanna let you know I’m thinking ‘bout you. I’m thinking ‘bout… you on this most historic of occasions. I’m thinking about you and Mom and Jeb and the whole thing.”<br><br>George did not know what he was saying, but it didn’t matter. The worst had already come to pass. Nothing could hurt him anymore. <br><br>“You know, I tried so hard to be just what you wanted. I went to Yale. I went into the Guard. I even did the oil thing. I did it all for you. And it never seemed to matter how hard I worked or how hard I tried. It was never good enough.” He chuckled and kicked his boot against the carpet. “I was always performin’, even as a little kid, y’know? I was always tryin’ to make people like you happy. And look where that got us?”<br><br>Something wet rolled down his cheeks. He wiped his eyes and continued grinning.<br><br>“Maybe I am a fuck-up. Maybe I am a black sheep and I don’t got the intellect of you or Jeb. I don’t care anymore. I’m tired, Poppy. I’m tired of doing all this shit to make other people happy. I love you, but if you can’t accept that I’m my own person with my own stuff, well…” He took a breath. “Well, you can go right to—.”<br><br>“Maximum voicemail length reached,” said a crisp mechanical voice in his ear. “Thank you for your call.”<br><br>There was a loud click and the line went dead. George continued to stare at the phone for several long seconds. Then, wordlessly, he slipped it into his pocket and stepped out of the dressing room. There were no aides to stop him as he took Laura by the arm. He kissed her gently on the head and, together, they walked out onto the stage to appear before the dismal crowd. He could not see their miserable faces, but maybe it was better that way. He did not try to imagine what the future held.</p>",
